				\begin{document}$$\bar 3\,\bar 3$$\end{document}) is particularly representative of the biexponential nature of the observed dynamics; it consists of a rapid decrease followed by a gradual increase in intensity. The plateau observed between +5 ps and +20 ps is indicative of the formation of the final fully-relaxed photoinduced HS state. Further supporting discussions are found in Supplementary Note 4 and Supplementary Note 5 wherein the biexponential fit in this BPY work is contrasted with the monoexponential fit in the previous UED work that studied the AZA molecular system (see Supplementary Fig. 2 and Supplementary Fig. 3).Fig. 3Photoinduced evolution of Bragg spots intensity.
a Short-time relative change in the intensity of select Bragg spots from t = −7 to 20 ps. b Global fitting of Bragg spots to show biexponential fit and monoexponential fit of relative intensity changes. c These intensity changes of the Bragg peaks are best modeled as a biexponential, with a (450 ± 23)-fs fast component and a (2.4 ± 0.4)-ps slow component. The solid lines represent the global fitting of the evolution of the intensity of the selected Bragg spots.
